= El senador de Michoacán

The Senate seats its new members this year, sixty-four of sixty-four for the party as always, and the arithmetic is beneath notice — except for one name your Michoacán people underline and pass around: Cuauhtémoc Cárdenas Solórzano, senator, forty-two, the general's son, who will hold the seat for approximately as long as it takes the President to find a better use for him.

He does not last the term. Within the year he is pulled into the cabinet as subsecretario of forestry — the system moving its promising men the way a chess player moves a piece it intends to need later, off the board's edge and into reserve. It is the most ordinary of PRI careers, and your analysts file it as such, with one dissenting footnote from an old agrarista who rode with the father: *watch the son. The father also spent years being useful to men who underestimated him.*

- @archivar_senador: A line in the file. The surname is not yet a politics — but it is not nothing, and the countryside remembers whose son he is.

@archivar_senador
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: political_capital += 1

Nothing is done and nothing needs to be. The page is opened; it will thicken on its own schedule, which is not yours. But when the break finally comes, a decade from now, you will not be starting the file from scratch — and in politics, as in intelligence, the difference between surprise and preparation is exactly one old man's footnote written early.

