= El gobernador que llega

The earthquake exposes the federal government the way the earthquake exposes everything — as a hollow façade held up by paint. De la Madrid vanishes for days; the army guards ruins instead of digging them; the state that spends a fortune insisting it is competent stands frozen while the city digs its own dead out with its own hands.

And into that vacuum, from Michoacán, comes a column of trucks nobody in the capital authorized: rescue teams, water, machinery, doctors — sent by the state's own governor, Cuauhtémoc Cárdenas, who did not ask Los Pinos whether he might help the capital because he already knew the answer and helped anyway. It is a small thing and an enormous one: a PRI governor behaving, in the one week the whole country was watching, as though government were for the governed.

The contrast writes itself, and the middle class — which had never once considered that the general's son might be more than a surname — considers it now. Your Michoacán cadres, who coordinated with his people in the rubble, come away with something no memo could give: the measure of the man, taken under a collapsed building at four in the morning, which is where all real measures are taken.

- @tender_puente: Deepen it. The rubble made allies of your people and his; build on the trust that only a disaster confers.
- @observar_gobernador: Note it, and wait. The break is coming; do not spend the relationship before it matters.

@tender_puente
go-to: post_event
choose-if: sup_colonos >= 10 or costureras >= 1
unavailable-subtitle: Building on the earthquake's trust needs your own people already in the rubble — the colonias, the costureras.
on-arrival: cd_rel += 1; sup_colonos += 2; political_capital += 2

The coordination outlasts the emergency, which is how you know it was real: the brigades your Movement fielded and the aid his government sent keep finding reasons to work the same colonias through the winter, and the habit of trust, once formed under a fallen roof, does not easily un-form. When the Corriente breaks two years from now, the bridge between the general's son and the organized left will not need building. It will only need crossing.

@observar_gobernador
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: political_capital += 1

You keep the distance a governing PRI-ista still requires, and the reasoning is sound: he is theirs until he is not, and premature embrace has ended more alliances than betrayal ever did. The file gains a page and the relationship gains a season of patience. When the break comes, you will be neither surprised nor compromised — the analyst's two favorite words.

