= Las senadurías

Whatever else the arithmetic of July was made to say, one number the machine could not fully swallow: the Federal District and Michoacán — the capital and the general's own ground — sent opposition senators to a chamber that had been unanimous for the party since 1929. Sixty years of a room where every hand went up together, ended by a count the regime spent everything to reverse and could not, quite, in the two places the wave ran deepest.

**[+ izq_senadores +] senators of the Frente** take the oath in a chamber visibly unsure how to seat them — there is no protocol for an opposition that exists. Muñoz Ledo among them, and the room learns the specific discomfort of a body that must now, occasionally, be argued with. It is not power. The PRI keeps its overwhelming majority, keeps the presidency it stole, keeps the machine. But the Senate — the last unanimous room in the Republic — has been made to hold a voice it did not authorize, and rooms, as the saying in your circles now goes, never go back.

- @tomar_protesta: Take the oath, and the tribune with it. Every session from here is one the regime cannot conduct in private.

@tomar_protesta
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: political_capital += 3; fe_voto += 1

The senators of the Frente are seated, sworn, and immediately inconvenient, which is the whole of the assignment. From the upper house's floor the fraud of July is entered into the record it was designed to escape; the disappeared of two decades are named where the Diario cannot decline to print them; and the country, watching a chamber it always knew was theatre discover it can be interrupted, learns the era's quiet lesson twice in one year: the machine can steal a count, but it can no longer steal the silence it used to count on.
